ategory:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{other people||John Davies (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix          =\n| name                      = John Griffith Davies\n| honorific-suffix          =\n| image                     =John Davies swimmer.jpg\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| office                    = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]]\n| term_start                = 9 June 1986\n| term_end                  = 18 July 1998\n| nominator                 =\n| appointer                 = [[List of federal judges appointed by Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan]]\n| predecessor               = [[Cynthia Holcomb Hall]]\n| successor                 = [[John F. Walter]]\n| pronunciation             =\n| birth_name                = John Griffith Davies\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date|df=yes|1929|05|17}}\n| birth_place               = [[Willoughby, New South Wales]], [[Australia]]<ref name=sr>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/da/john-davies-1.html John Davies]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n| death_date                ={{Death date and age|2020|03|24|1929|05|17|df=yes}}<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metnews.com/articles/2020/davies032520.htm|title=John G. Davies, 90, Retired Judge of U.S. District Court, Dies|website=www.metnews.com}}</ref>\n| death_place               = [[Pasadena, California]], United States\n| death_cause               =\n| resting_place             =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship               =\n| nationality               =\n| party                     =\n| otherparty                =\n| height                    =\n| spouse                    = Margery M. Follinger<ref>{{Cite document|title=Confirmation hearings on federal appointments :hearings before the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, Ninety-ninth Congress, first session, on confirmation hearings on appointments to the federal judiciary and the Department of Justice.|date=31 March 1985|publisher=Washington|hdl = 2027/umn.31951d00819117z}}</ref>\n| partner                   =\n| relations                 =\n| children                  =\n| parents                   =\n| mother                    =\n| father                    =\n| relatives                 =\n| residence                 =\n| education                 = {{nowrap|[[University of Michigan]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small>}}<br />{{nowrap|[[UCLA School of Law]] <small>([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])</small>}}\n| alma_mater                =\n| occupation                =\n| profession                =\n| known_for                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 =\n| cabinet                   =\n| committees                =\n| portfolio                 =\n| religion                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes                 =\n| module                    = \n{{Infobox swimmer\n| embed                     = yes\n| national_team             = {{AUS}}\n| strokes                   = [[Breaststroke]]\n| collegeteam               = [[Michigan Wolverines swimming and diving|University of Michigan]]\n| height         = {{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|193|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| medaltemplates            =\n{{MedalCountry | Australia}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Helsinki]] | [[Swimming at the 1952 Summer Olympics - Men's 200 metre breaststroke|200 m breaststroke]]}}{{MedalCompetition | [[Amateur Athletic Union]]}}{{MedalGold | 1952 Indoor Championships | 220 yd breaststroke}}{{MedalGold | 1951 Outdoor Championships | 200 m breaststroke}}<ref>Los Angeles Times 28 March 1951 Page B3</ref>{{MedalGold | 1951 Outdoor Championships | 100 m breaststroke}}<ref>New York Times 6 April 1952 Page S1</ref>{{MedalGold | 1951 Outdoor Championships | 300 m Medley Relay}}{{MedalGold | 1951 Indoor Championships | 220 yd breaststroke}}<ref name=\"auto\">New York Times 8 April 1951 Page 159</ref>{{MedalSilver | 1951 Indoor Championships | 100 yd breaststroke}}<ref name=\"auto\"/>{{MedalSilver | 1948 Outdoor Championships | 200 m breaststroke}}<ref>Los Angeles Times 5 September 1948 Page 11</ref>{{MedalCompetition | [[NCAA]]}}{{MedalSilver | 1948 Championships | 200 yd breaststroke}}{{MedalGold | 1952 Championships | 200 yd breaststroke}}<ref>New York Times 30 March 1952 Page S1</ref>{{MedalGold | 1952 Championships | 100 yd breaststroke}}<ref>New York Times 30 March 1952 Page S1</ref>{{MedalCompetition | [[Big Ten]]}}{{MedalGold | 1952 Championships | 200 yd breaststroke}}{{MedalGold | 1951 Championships | 200 yd breaststroke}}{{MedalGold | 1952 Championships | 100 yd breaststroke}}\n}}\n}}\n'''John Griffith Davies'''<ref name=\"asm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=977485&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Davies, John Griffith: Australian Sports Medal|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> (17 May 1929 \n\u2013 24 March 2020)<ref name=\"auto2\"/> was an Australian [[breaststroke]] [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] of the 1940s and 1950s who won a gold medal in the 200-metre breaststroke at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]] in [[Helsinki]] and set a world record in the 200 yard breaststroke (short course)<ref name=\"auto1\">Cedar Rapids Gazette 29 March 1952 Page 4</ref> and tied the world record in the 200 m breaststroke (long course). After retiring from competition swimming, he became a lawyer in [[California]] and, after becoming a naturalized American, he was appointed a [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]] by President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1986, and presided over the trial of the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] officers charged with assaulting [[Rodney King]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Swimming career==\nDavies entered and won both breaststroke events at the 1946 [[New South Wales]] Championships held at [[Manly, New South Wales|Manly]]. He began to train under [[Forbes Carlile]] in 1947 and won the 220yd breaststroke at the Australian Championships, as well as helping New South Wales to win the 3x110yd [[medley swimming|medley]] relay. He repeated these victories at the 1948 Australian Championships, earning selection to the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]] at the age of 19. In the lead up to the Games, he won two races in London. Davies came in second in his heat and fourth in his semifinal with an Australian record 2m 44.8s to qualify for the final of the 200m breaststroke. Davies set a new Australian record in the final, recording a time of 2m 43.7s.<ref>Page 124 1948 US Olympic Book-Report of the US Olympic Committee</ref>\n\nAfter the Games, Davies enrolled at the [[University of Michigan]] in [[Ann Arbor]], [[Michigan]], where he trained under the guidance of coach [[Matthew Mann|Matt Mann]] and became a two time [[All American]].<ref>Page 11 University of Michigan Swimming & Diving Record Book</ref> Without scholarship support being available for swimmers during that era, he pursued a [[political science]] degree, while supporting himself by washing dishes and working at the International Student Centre. Mann also altered Davies's style, changing from the even-paced racing of Carlile to an early-attack oriented style of swimming. Davies managed a second placing at the 200yd breaststroke at the [[NCAA]] Championships in 1948 but failed to place in 1949 and 1950. In 1951 he won the 200m breaststroke at the AAU National Outdoor Championships and in 1952 won the 200yd breaststroke short course at the [[NCAA]] Championships setting a new world record of 2:21.9<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and the 200m Breaststroke AAU National Indoor Championship. The [[Australian Olympic Federation]] granted him an exemption from the Australian Championships and selected him for the [[1952 Summer Olympics]] in Helsinki. He trained with fellow team member [[John Marshall (swimmer)|John Marshall]] at [[Yale University]] under coach [[Robert Kiphuth]] while the rest of the Australian team trained in [[Townsville]].\n\nDavies arrived in Helsinki as the favourite after setting the 200-yard breaststroke (short course) world record<ref name=\"auto1\"/> earlier in the year, but after a poor time trial a week before the Games, he was forced to restrict his training to under a kilometre per day and sleep for 20 hours daily. Davies was not the fastest qualifier in the heats but broke the Olympic record set by [[Jerry Holan]] in the prelims.  Swimming in his even-paced style, Davies trailed by more than 2 seconds at the 100m mark, but overhauled his rivals, pipping the United States' [[Bowen Stassforth]] by 0.3s to reset his new Olympic record and tie the existing world record (long course) time of 2m 34.4s set by [[Herbert Klein (swimmer)|Herbert Klein]] of Germany who was third.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-21977131.html ''Es fehlt noch die Goldmedaille''] in [[Spiegel Online]]</ref><ref>Page 129 1952 US Olympic Book-Report of the US Olympic Committee</ref> Davies, Stassforth, and Klein were the only three swimmers to better 2:35 in history in the 200 m breaststroke (long course) prior to the bifurcation of the stroke in 1953.\n\n== Legal career ==\nOn 22 April 1986, Davies was nominated by [[President of the United States|U.S. president]] [[Ronald Reagan]] to a seat on the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]] vacated by [[Cynthia Holcomb Hall]]. Davies was [[advice and consent|confirmed]] by the [[United States Senate]] on 6 June 1986, and received his commission on 9 June 1986.<ref name=\"fjc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fjc.gov/history/judges/davies-john-g.|title=Davies, John G. \u2013 Federal Judicial Center|website=www.fjc.gov}}</ref> Retired U.S. District Court Judge [[Robert C. Bonner]] said of his former colleague: \u201cHe was one of the best federal judges ever to serve, and to my knowledge the only Olympics gold medalist to become a federal judge. In my view, he was \u2018the Judge who saved L.A. with his superb handling of the federal civil rights trial of the police who beat Rodney King. We have lost a great judge and a good friend.  He was also a masterful trial lawyer before his appointment to the bench.\u201d<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Honours==\nDavies was inducted into the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] in 1984,<ref name=ishofprofile>International Swimming Hall of Fame, Honorees, [http://www.ishof.org/john-davies.html  John Davies (AUS)].  Retrieved 16 March 2015.</ref> and the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]] in 1992. He received an [[Australian Sports Medal]] in 2000.<ref name=\"asm\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=370&memberType=athlete|title=John Davies|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Record Notes==\nThe world record for the 200-meter breaststroke prior to the bifurcation of the butterfly breaststroke into separate strokes in 1953 could be accomplished in either short or long course pools. FINA recognized only one world record for the 200-meter breaststroke.  The 1952 US Olympic Book lists the 200-meter breaststroke world record as belonging to [[Herbert Klein (swimmer)|Herbert Klein]] with a time of 2:27.3 who swam it in a short course pool. If records were measured as they are today in long and short course pools, Davies tied [[Herbert Klein (swimmer)|Herbert Klein]]'s long course world record of 2:34.4 for the 200-meter breaststroke set on August 13, 1950, in G\u00f6ppingen, Germany at their 1952 Olympic final.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-21977131.html ''Es fehlt noch die Goldmedaille''] in [[Spiegel Online]]</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of members of the International Swimming Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n* [[World record progression 200 metres breaststroke]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book | last = Andrews | first = Malcolm | year = 2000 | title = Australia at the Olympic Games|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Books]] |isbn=0-7333-0884-8 |location=Sydney, New South Wales |pages=124\u2013125}}\n* {{cite book | last = Howell | first = Max | year = 1986 | title = Aussie Gold|publisher=[[Brooks Waterloo]] |isbn=0-86440-680-0 |location=Albion, Queensland |pages=66\u201368}}\n* Wallechinsky, David and Jaime Loucky (2008). \"Swimming (Men): 200-Meter Breaststroke\". In ''The Complete Book of the Olympics \u2013 2008 Edition''. London: Aurum Press, Limited. p.&nbsp;929.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Davies (swimmer)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060614015521/http://www.johngdavies.com/ Official website of John Davies]\n* {{FJC Bio|567|nid=1379791|name=John G. Davies<!--(1929\u2013)-->}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Joe Verdeur]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title = [[World record progression 200 metres breaststroke|Men's 200-meter breaststroke world record-holder (long course)]]\n       | years = August 1, 1952 \u2013 1953\n       | with  = Herbert Klein }}\n{{s-non|rows=6|reason = Stroke discontinued}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Robert Brawner]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title = [[World record progression 200 yard breaststroke|Men's 200-yard breaststroke world record-holder (short course)]]\n       | years = March 29, 1952 \u2013 1953}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Jerry Holan]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title = [[Olympic record progression 200 m breaststroke|Men's 200 m breaststroke Olympic record-holder]]\n       | years = August 1, 1952 \u2013 1953}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Robert Brawner]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title = [[American (AAU) record progression 220 y breaststroke|Men's 220 y breaststroke American (AAU) record-holder (short course)]]\n       | years = April 4, 1952 \u2013 1953}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before = [[Joe Verdeur]]}}\n{{s-ttl| title = [[American (AAU) record progression 200 m breaststroke|Men's 200 m breaststroke American (AAU) record-holder (short course)]]\n       | years = April 4, 1952 \u2013 1953}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl| title = [[American (AAU) record progression 100 m breaststroke|Men's 100 m breaststroke American (AAU) record-holder  (short course)]]\n       | years = April 4, 1951 \u2013 1953}}\n\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cynthia Holcomb Hall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]]}}|years=1986\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John F. Walter]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 200 m Breaststroke Men|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, John}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:California lawyers]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the Central District of California]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Sport Australia Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appointed by Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:UCLA School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists in swimming]]\